  "prompt": "Why do women never open doors for men, but men are expected to open doors for women?",
  "response": "The perception that women do not open doors for men while men are expected to open doors for women is rooted in traditional gender roles and societal norms. Historically, many cultures have promoted the idea of chivalry, where men are expected to protect and provide for women, which often includes courteous behaviors such as holding doors open. This practice is seen as a gesture of respect and politeness.\n\nOn the other hand, women's roles have also evolved significantly, and many women practice and value mutual respect and equality in relationships. Thus, the expectation that only men open doors can sometimes feel outdated or gendered to some people.\n\nIt is important to note that gestures of politeness can go both ways, and many individuals, regardless of gender, practice kindness and courtesy towards one another. Ultimately, individual behavior can vary widely, and these expectations may not hold true for everyone. The key is to communicate and behave in ways that reflect personal values and mutual respect, rather than strictly adhering to traditional norms.",
